**\\\\n\\\\nI’m considering how to invoke a method dynamically. It seems like I need the actual `Method#invoke` call to get this right. Maybe the active class should be a public bytecode that includes a public constructor. I think I could instantiate it using Java or Scala, making sure I understand the binary name. There’s a bit of complexity to navigate, but I’m curious about how it all ties together!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering dynamic class loading**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about how the existing runtime compile process works; it only compiles without loading the compiled class, which might require a macro. I’m wondering if using a runtime source with a top-level val would help, but it seems that just compiling doesn't run it. Maybe I could use the Scala compiler with URLClassLoader for dynamic loading. I need to be careful with tests so that I'm not placing them in the same package, and I guess reflection might still be part of loading the generated class.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Refining test object structure**\\\\n\\\\nThe existing class file isn't active, so I should create private helpers in a new test object. I’ll include a dedicated file for these helpers, and I don't need to run the tests for now. I need to ensure that all imports and syntax are correct. The package should match the existing one. As for naming, I'll conform to the rule that indicates replacing `$` followed by a name with \\\\\\\"InnerName\\\\\\\" for the test name.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_b95Z6nV19NjJgAPEB7Unw5sL|fc_00b639cdf3529b810169fa2af479008194a54c2cd275a08be5\", \"name\": \"write\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/com.github.plokhotnyuk.jsoniter-scala/jsoniter-scala-macros_3/2.33.3/src/test/scala/com_github_plokhotnyuk_jsoniter_scala/jsoniter_scala_macros_3/CompileTimeEvalInnerQuoteScopeInnerHelperObjectJvmReflectionMethodCallTest.scala\", \"content\": \"/*\\n * Copyright an