dFeature errors. If the image already includes the Scala compiler classes, runtime compilation may work. I wonder if an assertion can ensure the macro output, but it might be risky with the singleton type. I could also use an inline macro at the type for better clarity.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring macro return types**\\\\n\\\\nI’m thinking about using a transparent inline definition for mappedName. Perhaps I could define it as `val mappedName: \\\\\\\"helper_value\\\\\\\" = Helper...mappedName`. I need to ensure the macro returns a singleton type. If I define `transparent inline def mappedName: String`, maybe it can be refined. I wonder if I can simplify it further by just using `transparent inline def mappedName = ${ mappedNameImpl }` without an explicit return type, but does the macro need a return type? That’s something to consider!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Inspecting errors and processes**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about the literal singleton, but I'm feeling a bit unsure about its necessity. It seems like maybe the phase compile support doesn't actually execute the process, so there wouldn't be an error; the usage could be expanding. If call.process throws an error, then the compiler will report a macro exception and mark hasErrors as true. That's good, but I really need to inspect the status further to clarify things.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_eCwLMzagfaS0ClGsZim6xTpn|fc_00b639cdf3529b810169fa2b0a916481948794494283f202ae\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"git status --short\"}, \"partialJson\": \"{\\\"command\\\":\\\"git status --short\\\"}\"}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 5366, \"output\": 587, \"cacheRead\": 21504, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 27457, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1778002686451, \"responseId\": \"resp_00b639cdf3529b810169fa2afef5948194856d1d7159e652f3\"}}\n1298:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering test execution and assertions**\\n\\nI’m thinking about adding or refining tests to ensure all dynamic access call sites are covered. This runtime JUnit test, at JVM, will compile and execute the process, while the agent coverage should occur during this execution. But with native images, I'm catching UnsupportedFeature errors. If the image already includes the Scala compiler classes, runtime compilation may work. I wonder if an assertion can ensure the macro output, but it might be risky with the singleton type. I could also use an inline macro at the type for better clarity.\\n\\n**Exploring macro return types**\\n\\nI’m thinking about using a transparent inline definition for mappedName. Perhaps I could define it as `val mappedName: \\\"helper_value\\\" = Helper...mappedName`. I need to ensure the macro returns a singleton type. If I define `transparent inline def mappedName: String`, maybe it can be refined. I wonder if I can simplify it further by just using `transparent inline def mappedName = ${ mappedNameImpl }` without an explicit return type, but does the macro need a return type? That’s something to consider!\\n\\n**Inspecting errors and processes**\\n\\nI'm thinking about the literal singleton, but I'm feeling a bit unsure about its necessity. It seems like maybe the phase compile support doesn't actually execute the process, so there wouldn't be an error; the usage could be expanding. If call.process throws an error, then the compiler will report a macro exception and mark hasErrors as true. That's good, but I really need to inspect the status further to clarify things.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_00b639cdf3529b810169fa2aff99488194ae237dd59b894e08\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\"